post_text:
Cambrian School District Schools has worked collaboratively, methodically, and strategically to determine the most feasible reopening model to begin the 2020-21 academic year using the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and state guidelines.

The 2020 school year will begin August 19th and is a robust online learning experience that will engage students 100% virtually and provide additional supports for students, staff, and families.

Cambrian School District posts District Reopening Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs) on our website. Visit www.cambriansd.org to view.

post_text:
Do you shop with Amazon? Did you know that by setting up Amazon Smile for the Cambrian Educational Foundation a percentage of your purchases can go back to the District?

To set this up on a PC:
1. Visit smile.amazon.com and login with existing Amazon account
2. Scroll down and type "Cambrian Educational Foundation" in the box to pick your charitable organization and click search
3. Click Select
4. Check the box to acknowledge that you must visit smile.amazon.com each time you shop.

Setting up on Mobile Phones:

Android: Using the Amazon App: https://www.amazon.com/b?ie=UTF8&node=15576745011
iOS: Currently, you cannot use the Amazon App, but you can still shop using Safari
1) Visit smile.amazon.com in Safari and login
2) Hit the share button at the bottom of your screen
3) Click Add to Home Screen

post_text: Big shout out to Reaching Out Emergency Food Program in San Jose for their help supplying nutritious food to needy Cambrian families. We encourage any family that is in need to visit the Reaching Out Food Center, 2315 Canoas Garden Avenue, San Jose, CA 95124, (408) 267-4691. They are open Wednesdays and Thursdays from 9:00 a.m. until 12 noon. Just bring a photo ID and a bill with your address on it. Note that Reaching Out does not register your personal information with the U.S. Government, and you will be given free, nutritious groceries no matter what.

post_text:
STANFORD MATHEMATICIAN VISITS STEINDORF

Steindorf STEAM Magnet School welcomed Dr. Jo Boaler (second from left) to their classrooms. She observed some math classes recently. (Seen here with teacher Dan Winsor, Assistant Superintendent Kristi Schwiebert and Principal Lisa MacFarland.) Dr Jo Boaler is the Nomellini & Olivier Professor of Education at Stanford University. She is author of 14 books, numerous articles and a White House presenter on women and girls. She was named by the BBC as one of the 8 educators “changing the face of education.”

post_text:
Righteous and Totally Tubular Skateboard Information Reading......By Melissa Schilling at Fammatre Elementary School

My students are seeking connection with subjects that really interest them. I decided to plan a 10-week unit around physical fitness, information reading and pop culture: Tony Hawk is the perfect hero for us to study.

Tony Hawk is widely considered to be one of the most successful and influential pioneers of modern vertical skateboarding. He has also been involved in various philanthropic activities, including his own Tony Hawk Foundation that helps to build skateparks in underprivileged areas.

My Skateboard Book Club book commercial presentations took place this morning. The students did an outstanding job synthesizing and summarizing what they learned and then created and presented engaging cereals and commercials based upon the books they read about Tony Hawk. I obtained skateboards via Donor's Choose as rewards for the top scores. Great job, kids!

Dear Cambrian Families,
I am eager to share a short video clip about another excellent Cambrian School--Farnham Elementary School. Farnham's outstanding staff and school community have created a unique, diverse, motivated learning environment with exceptional opportunities. Children come from every corner of the globe and make up an engaged, energetic school population, eager to learn. Extensive collaboration takes place at Farnham--parents and highly trained staff have proven to go to great lengths to contribute in valuable ways to enhance every aspect of the school.

Take a look--learn more about Farnham Elementary School. As enrollment begins for the 2020-2021 school year, I encourage you to pass this video along to family and friends to consider Farnham. Together, we are Cambrian!

Sincerely,

Dr. Carrie Andrews, CSD Sup[erintendent

He gets a lot of support from the community stopping by. The last 3 years he earned the Blue Dimond award from Second Harvest Food Bank. He has filled 3 barrels this year. Look for a video about him on the Second Harvest Food Bank on Giving Tuesday in December.
GREAT JOB, NIMA!

post_text:
Farnham's One Warm Coat drive ended this past Friday, and we were truly overwhelmed by the generosity of our Farnham families! Over the course of two weeks, we collected over 400 items from our school community!

Here are some details:
- 43 winter hats
- 22 pairs of mittens/gloves
- 13 scarves
- 7 pairs of ski pants
- 39 adult coats
- 45 adult sweaters/sweatshirts
- 85 kid coats
- 129 kid sweaters/sweatshirts
- 17 sun protection hats
- a bag of miscellaneous clothing

These items have been sorted, packaged, labeled, and dropped off at Sacred Heart Community Services in San Jose. They will be distributed to local families this season through the organization's Clothes Closet. For more information on Sacred Heart Community Services, please check out their website at https://sacredheartcs.org/.

Thank you so much to all our families for sharing so many wonderful and warm items during our drive. Your generosity and kindness are deeply appreciated!
